content:
ASIA-PAC

New Zealand Retail Sales Ex. Inflation (Q3) Q/Q 0.0% vs. Exp. 1.0% (Prev. 1.1%). (Newswires)
 

UK/EU

The European Council released its statement that endorsed UK PM May’s Brexit deal as expected, while the EC restated determination to have a close as possible future partnership with the UK in line with the Political Declaration. (Newswires)

UK Cabinet ministers and EU diplomats are reportedly drawing up a “Plan B” proposal based on assumption PM May’s deal will fail to get through Parliament. (Telegraph)

UK PM May said on Friday that if we went back to EU after losing vote, the EU will not give us more and that there would be no-Brexit in her view. In other news, PM May was said to demand a Brexit TV debate with Labour leader Corbyn, while Scottish First Minister Sturgeon reportedly challenged the PM to a Brexit debate. (Newswires/Telegraph)

UK Foreign Secretary Jeremy Hunt said it is going to be challenging for PM May to secure support for the Brexit deal as the DUP has vowed to oppose her. (Independent)

UK government is reportedly to propose new limits on low-skilled migrants which is seen as a political move to win over Eurosceptics. (Telegraph)

Spanish government spokeswoman reiterated on Friday that any decisions about future status of Gibraltar in Brexit agreement must be approved by Spain, while Spain also insisted guarantees about Gibraltar's future should be part of the Brexit treaty and was said reject the solution of a political declaration; according to a government source. (Newswires)

It was reported on Friday that Italy's EU Affairs Minister Savona was said to be thinking about resigning in dissent over the government's challenge to EU budget rules, although there were later reports that Italy's Deputy PM Salvini spoke to EU Affair Minister Savona and does not believe he is planning to quit. (Newswires)

Italian Deputy PM Salvini threatened to bring down the government if coalition’s budget deficit target was changed. However, there were conflicting reports which suggested Salvini hinted of some room for compromise in which he stated that nobody is fixated on 2.4% budget deficit and that if there's a budget that makes the country grow, it could be 2.2% or 2.6%. (Newswires)

MARKET RECAP

Rockwell Collins (COL) was a top mover today after Chinese regulators gave the go ahead for United Technologies (UTX) to acquire it, United rose on the news too. Airlines traded higher today following the sharp sell-off in crude prices including stocks such as Delta Air Lines (DAL), American Airlines (AAL) and United Airlines (UAL). On the other side of the crude sell-off the energy sector got slammed across the board, Chevron (CVX), Exxon Mobil (XOM), EOG Resources (EOG) and Conoco Phillips (COP) were all weighing down the group. Facebook (FB) was also a bottom mover as its political scandals remain present in news flow. SPX -0.65% at 2632, NDX -0.73% at 6527, DJI -0.73% at 24286.

Treasuries were mixed, with the T-Note drifting slightly higher in thin-liquidity conditions. The upward momentum was inspired by pre-market risk off, as equity futures and, crucially, crude futures, were on the back foot. Moves were small, however, and as we leave for the weekend, the Z18 contract is knocking in the middle of the day's range (11904 to 119-15). T-notes (Z8) settled 1+ tick higher at 119-09.
